1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,820
Let's continue our journey into NLP.

2
00:00:01,820 --> 00:00:03,780
Today, we're going to look at the RNN architecture.

3
00:00:03,780 --> 00:00:06,200
It allows the model to move beyond just understanding words,

4
00:00:06,200 --> 00:00:08,760
to the point where it can understand entire sentences.

5
00:00:08,760 --> 00:00:11,500
In the last video, we introduced the concept of embedding.

6
00:00:11,500 --> 00:00:13,940
It can take discrete text labels

7
00:00:13,940 --> 00:00:17,000
represented as numbers within a continuous vector space.

8
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:18,340
This makes them computable.

9
00:00:18,340 --> 00:00:21,020
And on top of that, it also carries some semantic meaning.

10
00:00:21,020 --> 00:00:23,060
So, words with similar meanings are closer to each other.

11
00:00:23,060 --> 00:00:24,150
and also computable.

12
00:00:24,150 --> 00:00:26,350
And just like that, the computer can understand words.

13
00:00:26,350 --> 00:00:29,810
Now, a sentence is obviously made up of a bunch of words.

14
00:00:29,810 --> 00:00:31,670
So, since the model can understand a single word,

15
00:00:31,670 --> 00:00:33,910
So, does that mean it can understand the entire sentence?

16
00:00:33,910 --> 00:00:35,190
But that's not actually the case.

17
00:00:35,190 --> 00:00:36,410
Let's look at a few examples.

18
00:00:36,410 --> 00:00:39,530
For example, take the sentences "I like watching this movie" and "I don't like watching this movie."

19
00:00:39,530 --> 00:00:41,950
If we just look at it from the perspective of embedding technology,

20
00:00:41,950 --> 00:00:43,730
These two sentences are very similar.

21
00:00:43,730 --> 00:00:46,380
Their vector spaces are almost identical.

22
00:00:46,380 --> 00:00:47,860
But the only difference is the addition of the word 'not'.

23
00:00:47,860 --> 00:00:50,150
But the meaning they convey is completely different.

24
00:00:50,150 --> 00:00:53,370
And then you have the difference between 'fighting the White Bone Spirit' and 'the White Bone Spirit fighting Sun Wukong'.

25
00:00:53,370 --> 00:00:56,080
Their embeddings are actually identical.

26
00:00:56,080 --> 00:00:57,240
The words themselves don't have that information.

27
00:00:57,240 --> 00:00:58,100
are exactly the same.

28
00:00:58,100 --> 00:00:59,920
However, because their order is different,

29
00:00:59,920 --> 00:01:02,220
This completely changes the subject and the object.

30
00:01:02,220 --> 00:01:05,980
Or take these two sentences: "Apple released a new product" and "I ate an apple."

31
00:01:05,980 --> 00:01:07,500
They both use the word 'apple'.

32
00:01:07,500 --> 00:01:09,220
But, in different contexts,

33
00:01:09,220 --> 00:01:11,479
the meanings they convey are completely different.

34
00:01:11,479 --> 00:01:13,039
For example, if we rely solely on embeddings,

35
00:01:13,039 --> 00:01:15,419
we can't really understand a complete sentence.

36
00:01:15,419 --> 00:01:18,199
It's not just about knowing which words are in a sentence.

37
00:01:18,199 --> 00:01:20,420
We also need to know the order of these words.

38
00:01:20,420 --> 00:01:21,940
and the context surrounding them.

39
00:01:21,940 --> 00:01:23,900
Only then can we accurately understand the sentence.

40
00:01:23,900 --> 00:01:25,900
So, you might be thinking, "Why not just use an FN?"

41
00:01:25,900 --> 00:01:28,500
So, could we just use a neural network to solve this problem?

42
00:01:28,500 --> 00:01:30,900
So first, let's take a look at what a feedforward neural network is.

43
00:01:30,900 --> 00:01:33,140
I'm sure when you've all seen the Transformer architecture,

44
00:01:33,140 --> 00:01:34,760
and at the end, there's also an FNN layer.

45
00:01:34,760 --> 00:01:36,380
And the reason it's called a 'feed-forward' network is...

46
00:01:36,380 --> 00:01:38,900
It's a type of network where information flows in one direction only.

47
00:01:38,900 --> 00:01:41,520
Does the front give feedback to the back?

48
00:01:41,520 --> 00:01:43,180
The data starts from the input layer,

49
00:01:43,180 --> 00:01:44,600
passing through the hidden layers,

50
00:01:44,600 --> 00:01:45,500
until it reaches the output layer.

51
00:01:45,500 --> 00:01:46,360
and makes a prediction.

52
00:01:46,360 --> 00:01:48,600
There are no recurrent connections within the network.

53
00:01:48,600 --> 00:01:50,240
It just keeps moving in a single direction.

54
00:01:50,240 --> 00:01:52,820
It doesn't loop back on itself and go through various cycles.

55
00:01:52,820 --> 00:01:56,710
The MLP we learned about earlier is a classic example of an FNN.

56
00:01:56,710 --> 00:01:59,230
But this kind of structure isn't really suitable for direct processing.

57
00:01:59,230 --> 00:02:02,390
There are two main reasons why it's not suited for natural language sequences.

58
00:02:02,920 --> 00:02:05,720
The first reason is that it can't model the dependencies between preceding and following words.

59
00:02:05,720 --> 00:02:07,180
Take our natural language sentences, for example.

60
00:02:07,180 --> 00:02:08,690
I'm going to the bank to deposit money.

61
00:02:08,690 --> 00:02:13,250
The meaning of the word 'bank' can only be determined by looking at the context that comes before it.

62
00:02:13,250 --> 00:02:15,310
There's a sequential relationship between them.

63
00:02:15,310 --> 00:02:18,680
Now, with a traditional approach, if we were to just flatten these words,

64
00:02:18,680 --> 00:02:19,400
and feed them into the network,

65
00:02:19,400 --> 00:02:20,240
and feed it in all at once,

66
00:02:20,240 --> 00:02:21,140
and get an output all at once.

67
00:02:21,140 --> 00:02:23,470
In reality, they don't capture this sequential order.

68
00:02:23,470 --> 00:02:25,150
the sequential order and dependencies between them.

69
00:02:25,150 --> 00:02:27,750
Instead, they just treat the entire sequence as a single, fixed vector.

70
00:02:27,750 --> 00:02:31,810
So, in this case, the architecture itself simply doesn't have that kind of mechanism.

71
00:02:31,810 --> 00:02:35,570
So, it just can't understand the sequential relationships between these words.

72
00:02:35,810 --> 00:02:36,890
And what's the other thing?

73
00:02:36,890 --> 00:02:38,970
Variable-length sequences are difficult to align with its fixed input.

74
00:02:38,970 --> 00:02:40,890
Now, we know that for the input to our neural network,

75
00:02:40,890 --> 00:02:42,250
is actually a fixed one.

76
00:02:42,250 --> 00:02:44,940
For instance, let's say we're talking about how many neurons we have in the first input layer.

77
00:02:44,940 --> 00:02:47,680
This determines the length of the input I can accept.

78
00:02:47,680 --> 00:02:51,830
But the thing is, for natural language sentences, their length is actually variable.

79
00:02:51,830 --> 00:02:53,590
Different sentences have different lengths.

80
00:02:53,590 --> 00:02:56,000
And of course, to force them to align,

81
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:58,260
So, when you want to use an FN to represent it,

82
00:02:58,260 --> 00:02:59,100
The inputs have to be the same.

83
00:02:59,100 --> 00:03:00,260
It's not that it's impossible, though.

84
00:03:00,260 --> 00:03:02,260
What I can do is set a fixed length.

85
00:03:02,260 --> 00:03:04,540
And for the parts that go over, I'll just truncate them.

86
00:03:04,540 --> 00:03:06,660
And for the next input, what if it's too short?

87
00:03:06,660 --> 00:03:08,600
I can just pad it to make up the difference.

88
00:03:08,600 --> 00:03:09,800
This also forces the sequences to be aligned.

89
00:03:09,800 --> 00:03:11,040
And just like that, it's ready for input.

90
00:03:11,040 --> 00:03:13,180
But truncation means you lose information.

91
00:03:13,180 --> 00:03:15,980
And if you pad it by filling in with empty spaces, you'll just introduce some noise.

92
00:03:15,980 --> 00:03:17,340
This affects the model's learning.

93
00:03:17,340 --> 00:03:20,220
This, in turn, makes the training process extremely difficult.

94
00:03:20,220 --> 00:03:22,690
So, since these methods can't solve the problem,

95
00:03:22,690 --> 00:03:23,530
So, what's the solution?

96
00:03:23,530 --> 00:03:26,910
So basically, what RNN did was make some changes to the overall approach.

97
00:03:26,910 --> 00:03:29,440
It didn't change the independent variables either.

98
00:03:29,440 --> 00:03:31,360
I mean, the word vectors, they stay exactly as they were.

99
00:03:31,360 --> 00:03:34,000
What it changes is how we read the sentence.

100
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:35,240
It's not like the old methods.

101
00:03:35,240 --> 00:03:37,780
Instead, it's about combining the entire sentence into a single, fixed vector.

102
00:03:37,780 --> 00:03:39,540
It reads the input sequentially, performing calculations layer by layer.

103
00:03:39,540 --> 00:03:40,500
and then spit out a result.

104
00:03:40,500 --> 00:03:41,860
So, how does it work?

105
00:03:41,860 --> 00:03:43,460
From left to right.

106
00:03:43,460 --> 00:03:44,260
one token at a time.

107
00:03:44,260 --> 00:03:45,320
reading one token at a time.

108
00:03:45,320 --> 00:03:46,660
When it reads the first word,

109
00:03:46,660 --> 00:03:49,720
it can only determine a state based on the current input.

110
00:03:49,720 --> 00:03:50,960
Then it moves on to the second word.

111
00:03:50,960 --> 00:03:51,920
So, it reads the, uh...

112
00:03:51,920 --> 00:03:53,160
The first thing it does is remember that word.

113
00:03:53,160 --> 00:03:54,720
and create a vectorized representation of it.

114
00:03:54,720 --> 00:03:56,120
Then, when it reads the second word,

115
00:03:56,120 --> 00:03:59,600
and combines it with the state representation from the previous step.

116
00:03:59,600 --> 00:04:00,400
and combine them.

117
00:04:00,400 --> 00:04:03,140
And based on these two, it then reads the third word.

118
00:04:03,140 --> 00:04:03,940
And it goes on, layer by layer.

119
00:04:03,940 --> 00:04:05,400
until it's completely processed.

120
00:04:05,400 --> 00:04:06,620
Let's look at a simple example.

121
00:04:06,620 --> 00:04:10,800
For example, let's say it needs to process the natural language sequence "I love nature."

122
00:04:10,800 --> 00:04:11,820
So, how does it read it?

123
00:04:11,820 --> 00:04:14,320
So, first, it only reads this one token, 'I'.

124
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:15,960
This is what we call a time step.

125
00:04:15,960 --> 00:04:18,140
Because, you know, it's a process that's completed in multiple steps.

126
00:04:18,140 --> 00:04:19,029
So, T equals one.

127
00:04:19,029 --> 00:04:21,989
So, after it's processed my input and formed an understanding,

128
00:04:21,989 --> 00:04:23,309
and store it somewhere.

129
00:04:23,309 --> 00:04:24,849
We call this the hidden state.

130
00:04:24,849 --> 00:04:26,269
We'll call this H1.

131
00:04:26,269 --> 00:04:27,720
So at this point, it knows the word is 'me'.

132
00:04:27,720 --> 00:04:30,630
Then, the second word, 'I', is fed in as the next input.

133
00:04:30,630 --> 00:04:31,990
So, when it's processing the 'I'...

134
00:04:31,990 --> 00:04:34,190
It remembers that the previous word was 'my'.

135
00:04:34,190 --> 00:04:35,990
So, it understands the word 'I' based on the context of 'my'.

136
00:04:35,990 --> 00:04:37,820
So it combines these two to understand the meaning.

137
00:04:37,820 --> 00:04:39,780
And just like that, it's remembered the sequence "I love."

138
00:04:39,780 --> 00:04:41,720
So, when it gets to the next word, 'nature'...

139
00:04:41,720 --> 00:04:43,540
and combine it with the words 'I love' and 'nature'.

140
00:04:43,540 --> 00:04:45,830
and it kind of puts two and two together, you know?

141
00:04:45,830 --> 00:04:47,210
and it understands the phrase 'I love nature'.

142
00:04:47,210 --> 00:04:48,070
So, during this process,

143
00:04:48,070 --> 00:04:50,050
In other words, with each step of the process,

144
00:04:50,050 --> 00:04:50,790
When it reads in one,

145
00:04:50,790 --> 00:04:52,380
it generates a hidden state.

146
00:04:52,380 --> 00:04:53,580
Then, when it reads the second one,

147
00:04:53,580 --> 00:04:55,860
it combines with the first hidden state.

148
00:04:55,860 --> 00:04:57,640
to produce the second hidden state.

149
00:04:57,640 --> 00:04:58,980
Then, it reads the third token.

150
00:04:58,980 --> 00:05:00,960
and then combines it with the second hidden state.

151
00:05:00,960 --> 00:05:02,300
to produce the third hidden state.

152
00:05:02,300 --> 00:05:04,900
This process continues until it reads the end-of-sequence token.

153
00:05:04,900 --> 00:05:06,240
the end of the sequence.

154
00:05:06,240 --> 00:05:08,400
And that final result is all that matters.

155
00:05:08,400 --> 00:05:09,500
to produce the final output.

156
00:05:09,500 --> 00:05:11,080
So, that's the basic idea.

157
00:05:11,080 --> 00:05:12,740
So, what exactly is this hidden state?

158
00:05:12,740 --> 00:05:14,660
So, in the logical deduction we just went through,

159
00:05:14,660 --> 00:05:16,880
It does give off a sense of memory, doesn't it?

160
00:05:16,880 --> 00:05:19,580
Well, mathematically speaking, it's actually a vector.

161
00:05:19,580 --> 00:05:21,620
represented by a vector with a fixed dimensionality.

162
00:05:21,620 --> 00:05:23,159
and it calculates a set of floating-point numbers.

163
00:05:23,159 --> 00:05:25,679
And this information is multidimensional.

164
00:05:25,679 --> 00:05:26,399
It's not that

165
00:05:26,399 --> 00:05:29,000
But it's not exactly the same as the embedding result either.

166
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:31,280
And it's not like each one of them corresponds to a single word.

167
00:05:31,280 --> 00:05:32,920
Together, they reflect the overall picture.

168
00:05:32,920 --> 00:05:35,650
This is the memory processing work I'm doing on your previous input.

169
00:05:35,650 --> 00:05:37,590
And it gets updated with each step.

170
00:05:37,590 --> 00:05:40,070
But its dimensionality doesn't change.

171
00:05:40,070 --> 00:05:41,490
Let me express this mathematically.

172
00:05:41,490 --> 00:05:44,480
So, for example, how is the hidden state at timestep T generated?

173
00:05:44,480 --> 00:05:45,500
is a function of...

174
00:05:45,500 --> 00:05:46,740
First, we have my input.

175
00:05:46,740 --> 00:05:47,810
my XT,

176
00:05:47,810 --> 00:05:48,690
So, step seven.

177
00:05:48,690 --> 00:05:51,730
So, I take my input and the hidden state from the previous step,

178
00:05:51,730 --> 00:05:53,620
and we perform a combined operation on them.

179
00:05:53,620 --> 00:05:56,780
And that gives us the new hidden state for this step.

180
00:05:56,780 --> 00:05:59,570
So, HT is the hidden state generated at step T.

181
00:05:59,570 --> 00:06:01,970
And XT is the current input.

182
00:06:01,970 --> 00:06:05,130
So, let's take the example again of the sentence, "I do not like this movie."

183
00:06:05,130 --> 00:06:06,290
So, how does this process work?

184
00:06:06,290 --> 00:06:09,470
First, at H0, the initial state could be all zeros.

185
00:06:09,470 --> 00:06:11,990
Or of course, it could also be a set of parameters from the model's training.

186
00:06:11,990 --> 00:06:12,820
Either way works.

187
00:06:12,820 --> 00:06:13,980
So, when T is equal to one...

188
00:06:13,980 --> 00:06:15,020
meaning there's no hidden state.

189
00:06:15,020 --> 00:06:17,780
I just need to input "OK," and it gets me.

190
00:06:17,780 --> 00:06:19,660
and puts it into the hidden state, H1.

191
00:06:19,660 --> 00:06:22,040
So, what we're actually doing is computing the hidden state for this step.

192
00:06:22,040 --> 00:06:23,540
And for the second step,

193
00:06:23,540 --> 00:06:25,680
So, by the second step, it has already understood me.

194
00:06:25,680 --> 00:06:26,120
Right?

195
00:06:26,120 --> 00:06:29,320
So it combines me and my input, which becomes my hidden state, right?

196
00:06:29,320 --> 00:06:30,460
It's about understanding me.

197
00:06:30,460 --> 00:06:33,560
So, it just goes on and on, using the result from the previous step in this process.

198
00:06:33,560 --> 00:06:35,600
Doesn't this feel familiar, especially if you're into programming?

199
00:06:35,600 --> 00:06:36,600
This should feel pretty familiar.

200
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:37,200
Right?

201
00:06:37,200 --> 00:06:38,980
This is actually kind of like recursion.

202
00:06:38,980 --> 00:06:39,940
is the hidden state.

203
00:06:39,940 --> 00:06:43,010
So basically, it represents, uh, the information from what I've read in before.

204
00:06:43,010 --> 00:06:43,950
understanding of a sequence.

205
00:06:43,950 --> 00:06:46,210
So, let's take a look at its entire cycle.

206
00:06:46,210 --> 00:06:49,770
So, maybe if we go back one step from T to the seventh step, the input at that point...

207
00:06:49,770 --> 00:06:51,750
So, at time step T minus one...

208
00:06:51,750 --> 00:06:54,920
and that gives us HT minus one, which is this hidden state.

209
00:06:54,920 --> 00:06:56,040
So, you can think of it as...

210
00:06:56,040 --> 00:06:59,169
I combine my previous memory point with my current input,

211
00:06:59,169 --> 00:07:01,069
to form my current memory point.

212
00:07:01,069 --> 00:07:03,590
and then process the next input.

213
00:07:03,590 --> 00:07:06,750
So, as you can see in the diagram, there are a lot of these RNN cells.

214
00:07:06,750 --> 00:07:08,550
So, for each of these processing steps...

215
00:07:08,550 --> 00:07:11,979
So, this whole process of processing the hidden state and the input...

216
00:07:11,979 --> 00:07:14,339
And we call this an RNN cell.

217
00:07:14,339 --> 00:07:15,699
They are all the same cell, you see.

218
00:07:15,699 --> 00:07:18,640
It's just that it's used repeatedly at different points in time.

219
00:07:18,640 --> 00:07:21,600
And this process, doesn't it look a lot like a loop?

220
00:07:21,600 --> 00:07:23,440
So, if we were to represent this in pseudocode...

221
00:07:23,440 --> 00:07:25,409
So, H0 is just the initialization.

222
00:07:25,409 --> 00:07:29,180
So, I'll just loop through, calling the RNN cell to process each token in the sequence.

223
00:07:29,180 --> 00:07:31,180
And with each processing step, we store that information in the hidden state.

224
00:07:31,180 --> 00:07:32,540
So, I'll use a while loop for the current input,

225
00:07:32,540 --> 00:07:34,460
as long as it's not the end of the sequence.

226
00:07:34,460 --> 00:07:36,689
until it's a continuous end-of-sequence token.

227
00:07:36,689 --> 00:07:39,789
So, what do I append to the current hidden state?

228
00:07:39,789 --> 00:07:41,420
So, for this RNN function...

229
00:07:41,420 --> 00:07:44,860
It takes the current input and the previous hidden state,

230
00:07:44,860 --> 00:07:46,300
and append it.

231
00:07:46,300 --> 00:07:48,060
and at T plus one, it processes the next step.

232
00:07:48,060 --> 00:07:49,760
And you just keep repeating this loop.

233
00:07:49,760 --> 00:07:53,400
And finally, let's say I'm ready to make an output.

234
00:07:53,400 --> 00:07:54,880
I've learned everything there is to learn.

235
00:07:54,880 --> 00:07:56,040
and then I can make the output, right?

236
00:07:56,040 --> 00:07:58,080
I don't need to wait until the very last hidden state.

237
00:07:58,080 --> 00:07:59,560
Once it's processed all the inputs,

238
00:07:59,560 --> 00:08:01,360
I can just use that final hidden state,

239
00:08:01,360 --> 00:08:04,580
and feed it into something called a task.

240
00:08:04,580 --> 00:08:06,120
and place it outside the loop.

241
00:08:06,120 --> 00:08:07,100
to make an overall prediction.

242
00:08:07,100 --> 00:08:09,900
And with that, I can make a prediction for the entire sequence.

243
00:08:09,900 --> 00:08:11,620
So, this is basically how an RNN works.

244
00:08:11,620 --> 00:08:12,980
This is the most basic workflow.

245
00:08:12,980 --> 00:08:16,100
Of course, we've also included the output for each step here.

246
00:08:16,100 --> 00:08:17,340
That is, the prediction at each step.

247
00:08:17,340 --> 00:08:19,540
But this step isn't always necessary, though.

248
00:08:19,540 --> 00:08:20,740
This depends on the specific task.

249
00:08:20,740 --> 00:08:22,940
Next, we'll cover the different types of tasks.

250
00:08:22,940 --> 00:08:24,930
The timing of its output is different.

251
00:08:24,930 --> 00:08:26,610
